The Way Out: Prologue.<br>
<br>
Imagine if you will a cool Autumn morning; the darkish coolness of that morning in a forest older than time. A stone bridge painted in the patina of ages, usually guarded by four stalwart Teir'Dal in armor, but empty - empty that is except for a knot of corpses.<br>
<br>
One is a woman; her face is twisted in hate and terror, the midnight skin greyish in death. The second lies face down, fingers clutching at the marbled flagstones in denial, his skin also indigo-grey. The last is pale and almost serene, though something of surprise lingers in his still countenance. His own hands grip the knife which is still hilt-deep in his breast.<br>
<br>
Now picture the living members of this scene; most are indecernable, a knot of black-clad shadow. A few stand out: a gnome, green-robed and gnarled, his head bowed in sorrow. A tall man with a painted face, his arms around a leather-clad elven woman as they both look on the corpses with expressionless features. And at the last, one other elf who kneels beside the third body, her face a caricature in dry-eyed grief.<br>
<br>
This one lifts bloody hands and wraps them around the hands and hilt, and tugs the knife free. She lets the knife fall, and holds the dead hands to her face a moment before placing them at the dead man's sides. Then she gets up and looks at the nervous shadowy audience, their shifting and whispering making them seem like a flock of uneasy ghosts.<br>
<br>
&quot;Its over,&quot; she says softly, and begins to move, the ghosts clearing her path away from the bridge with alacrity that could either be respect or fear.<br>
<br>
From a great distance, his vision enhanced magically, the red-robed magician watches. &quot;But no, my little rogue, how very wrong you are. It merely begins.&quot;<br>
<br>
------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Merri stared at the jug of mead in front of her, as though it contained all the combined world's wisdom - which, if you listed to drunken old Fraser, down at the end of the bar,  it just might - but pushed it aside. Her head swam enough, her chest tight and seeming unwilling to breathe, her stomach throbbed with nervous knots. Mead would only increase those displeasureable feelings unless she all but drowned herself in it.<br>
<br>
&quot;Drowned...&quot; she murmured softly, slowly turning the green glass vessel in her hands and watching the tawny liquor inside slosh in little wavelets. &quot;Hey Scon -&quot;<br>
<br>
The barkeep looked up, an eyebrow lifted. His elven customer hadn't had a drink in the three hours she'd sat quietly at the end of the bar, but her voice wavered unsteadily. &quot;Aye Merri? Somethin' wrong wit' the mead?&quot;<br>
<br>
The elf shook her head, and pushed the bottle aside again. &quot;Not at all, Scon; just wanted to know. Anyone ever drowned out there in the Nest?&quot; She paused a moment, looking back at her distorted reflection in the green glass bottle. &quot;Must be an interesting way to die, drowning...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Aye. Many a gnoll. Th' 'ccasional orc. One 'r two unwary foreigners, though most take the Gwen; and none o' our own folk in living memory. Why d'ya ask?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Just wondered what it would be like. To drown, I mean..&quot;<br>
<br>
Scon McDaniel regarded the tiny (in comparison) being who perched at the end of his bar with a barbarian's typically frank appraisal. She had hair of sunny blonde, eyes like a clear winter sky when you look straight up. Her petite body held no spare flesh, only muscles and lines of use. Her face looked as though it should smile ... but it wasn't. The only time Scon had seen her smile, she had been taking her dagger out of an Orc Trooper's spine. The smile had faded quickly when she realised the beast's bones had notched her blade.<br>
<br>
&quot;It's no' pleasant at all. A man's lungs fill up with water, and he strangles. I've seen faces of them as drowned, they aren't peaceful.&quot; Scon polished a pewter tankard with his apron and set it up next to her bottle of mead.<br>
<br>
Merri regarded him a long moment, then tipped the bottle out into the tankard and lifted it to her lips. &quot;If thats how it is, Scon, then I'm drowning on dry land. Better get me another mead.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
