</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/bthesafehouse.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=merribelle>Merribelle</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(12/17/00 7:40:50 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> The Way Out : Chaper One.</span><hr size=1> Merri dug her spikes more firmly into the icy surface of the river and kept moving, ignoring the bitter wind that was pushing at her. A fist, cold and mailed with ice, that's how the wind seemed. The cold was poisonous enough on its own, a seeping chill that tied her catlike muscles in rigid knots, without the wind that tore at her eyes and hair and burned her lungs.<br>
<br>
&quot;Damn you, Grehan. Get yourself lost and killed out here in this frozen hell, next time. Don't get me involved in whatever passes for intrigue among you, just bloody die!&quot; The words were bitter but meaningless. Grehan trudged a few feet behind her, and wouldn't have heard her over the howling wind, but wouldn't have cared if he had. Merri knew that. She winced as the wind blew her hood against her cheek, for the fur of her hood-lining was frosted around the edges in a fringe of tiny icicles. Despite the double-thickness mittens, her hands were numbing faster than her elven circulation could prevent. <br>
<br>
Merri cursed colorfully and reached into her tunic for the silver flask she kept there. Her body heat had kept it warmer than she'd hoped, and the liquor inside was fire which sprang instantly through her veins. <br>
The flask was snatched out of her hands after only a swallow of the warm ginesh. <br>
<br>
Grehan stared at her, iceblue eyes hard, looking too much like the frozen river they had followed doggedly through this near-blizzard. &quot;No more,&quot; he rasped, the cold obviously no easier for him than for Merri. &quot;More than enough to warm you and it will kill you out here, drive the moisture out of you and kill you.&quot; He took a single sip for himself and handed back the flask, waiting until she nodded before he released it.<br>
<br>
Scowling, Merribelle slid the flask back into her tunic, wincing slightly at the chill even that brief moment in the open had imparted to the metal. The curved flask sat comfortably against her breast, the inner layer of fur on her tunic cushioning it from movement. Resolutely lacing the tunic up till it caught uncomfortably under her chin, she turned one final glare on her companion and moved on, digging her feet into the frozen water angrily.<br>
<br>
A fine thing this, wasn't it? Merribelle, rogue of middle rank, called &quot;Stealshearts&quot; by those who knew her. Used to a warm taproom and sunlit fields, or even black caverns and bloody fights. And where was she? Why, trudging down a river in the middle of Everfrost, freezing slowly and getting angrier by the moment. And for what purpose?<br>
<br>
To find something that didn't exist, if you listened to those who should know. Chasing a phantom through a howling blizzard with noone but an apprentice rogue at her back and nothing but a flask of Ginesh to keep her from becoming a block of this same wretched ice she was walking on. Seething with frustration and rage, and not realising it was keeping her warmer, she swore again, in Barbarian so Grehan could not mistake her ire.<br>
<br>
Grehan knew her temper, and knew that when they finally reached the Nest again she'd be livid. The next poor fool in McDaniels who got drunk enough to be curious what elf women kissed like would probably be missing both ears and both hands come morning.  Merri was close to a legend in Scon's tavern, but every night someone had a wee bit much and forgot why. <br>
<br>
Grehan could only hope that tonight the liquor would get the better of her, and that he and Scatha could carry her up to her bed and lock the door to save some poor nitwit from carstration or worse. In the meantime he just had to cope with a string of invective icier than the wind, and comfort himself that by morning she'd have forgiven him this fool's errand.<br>
<br>
&quot;Remind me again, Grehan, just <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> why</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> I'm out here?&quot; he heard her shout, and sighed. Perhaps it would not be the morning, after all. <br>
<br>
*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*<br>
<br>
&quot;T'is not a man yer lookin' fer, lad&quot; the old woman had said, her grin nearly toothless as she smiled at him. &quot;T'is a woman, an' a legend at that. Aeron was a legend when I was birthed, an' she no more than 18. But what else could y' expect from a lass whose name in the old tongue means <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Goddess of Slaughter</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;But surely she's dead now, old mother, if she was a woman already when you were born?&quot; Grehan had looked skeptical, and the woman turned to look at Merri with eyes that were faded emeralds, like emeralds under ice.<br>
<br>
&quot;Nay, lad, some of us have the power t' live beyond the means of others. I've been naught all m' life but a wife an' mother, worthy and fine though they be. But those o' spirit who lift dagger fer true cause can live way beyond the times of the rest of us. Ask yer elfish friend, there. Her people live decades to my years. No, lad, Aeron lives yet, and she's out there. Much like Karg and his ilk, she wanders the snow, keepin’ her wits and wiles sharp, keepin’ back the rage that’s her birthright an’ curse.” Again the old woman’s eyes flicked to Merri where she sat, and for the first time spoke directly to her. “You know that rage, don’ ye, elf-lass? Aye, ye do. An old woman can see it – and so will Aeron.”<br>
<br>
The door flung open, the old woman’s hut suddenly chill with the influx of icy air, and Cappi McTarnigal stood in the door with two others at his back. Merri looked up at them, unimpressed, while Grehan stumbled to his feet, knocking the stool over that had supported him.<br>
<br>
“Keep yer peace, old woman. Fillin’ the lad’s head with snowblind fantasies, and tellin’ mead-talk to strangers.” Cappi scowled at Merribelle openly, distrusting both her foreign blood and her status as a rogue. “Ye’ve been told before ter keep yer mouth shut. Now I’ll tell y’ again: Aeron Aodann is dead and buried, an’ the stories you spout deader still. There is no point to yer senile ramblings.”<br>
<br>
The old woman looked up at McTarnigal, and laughed, a horrid empty sound which was not humor. “Still ‘feared of the White Rose, Cappi? Still watchin’ yer back for the old legends ter take back what ye and yer kindred buried? Hah, but y’ know an ol’ woman has naught ter fear, an’ no reason to stop tellin’ “stories” ter young folk… why should the great McTarnigal care, eh? Unless there were truth in the tales?” Still cackling, the old woman looked across at Merribelle.<br>
<br>
“Ye see, elf-lass, Aeron Aodann was Lady of the Halas rogues, they called her the White Rose, as all her students are called now. She wielded two daggers made of runed white metal, with roses ‘grained into their hilts, and a fightin’ fury as makes the wolf-wild pale in comparison. McTarnigal’s grandfather was her second, wasn’t he Cappi? Right up ‘till the time she took off ter fight the dark folk an’ he took over –“<br>
<br>
“Silence!” McTarnigal growled, his expression so deeply angry that Merri almost missed the uncertainty in his eyes. “Grehan, yer late f’r patrol duty. An’ I think yer foreign wench will be missin’ her stool at the tavern.” <br>
<br>
Grehan scuttled out, glancing apologetically at Merri for the insult. The old woman watched him go, calmly, then fastened her old hand clawlike on McTarnigal’s wrist as he turned to follow. “Yer a fool ter stop me talkin’ of it, Cappi. Y’ll only make the boy want it worse… but yer already too late to hush him, fer he’s seen Aeron Aodann, and she’s seen him. Naught ye can do now but wait. The White Rose returns, Cappi. Wait for her to come back…”<br>
<br>
*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*^*<br>
<br>
Grehan gritted his teeth as a blast of especially cold air hit him, almost pushing him back down the bank to the frozen river he and Merri had just left. Digging his spiked boots deeper into the icy ground and leaning on the haft of his spear, he hauled himself up the steep incline after Merri, whose catlike agility had her up the bank much quicker than he. Keeping his head down, he almost collided with the elf, who stood stock still on the very edge of the embankment.<br>
<br>
“Merri?” He peered off into the distance, off into the swirling whiteness that held the wood-elf’s gaze, but could see nothing but the twisting billows of snow and wind. He squinted, trying to sharpen his gaze, but it didn’t help. <br>
<br>
Merribelle watched the figure only she could see move inorexably out of the blizzard towards her, slow and determined, inevitable as a tide. The wind didn’t seem to bother whoever it was. As the shape came closer Merri could make out some details: the thick silver fur of wolf-pelt protruding from the hood which rimmed features still indistinct, the deliberate silence and majesty of the stride despite the spiked heavy boots. <br>
<br>
Grehan lifted a hand to Merri’s arm, now seeing the outline of the figure approaching, and his barbarian features were pale against his clanmark’s blue spiral. Merri ignored him and stepped forwards, catching sight of the face within the hood. A woman of Grehan’s own people, no clan-mark or battle paint. Lovely, with ice-blue eyes and hair like sunset-touched gold. And riding the belt around the woman’s hips, two white daggers, with roses carved into them.<br>
<br>
“Aeron Aodann” Grehan whispered, clenching his fingers, numb as they were, tighter around shaft of his spear. This was who he’d come out here to find, spurred on by his grandmother’s tales. But Aeron wasn’t looking at him, but at the elf who stood implacably before her.<br>
<br>
Merribelle watched the woman come up to them, her countenance unreadable. Then without taking her eyes off Aeron’s face, she bowed slightly, a measure of respect. Aeron nodded back, then flicked a glance at Grehan before smiling down at the elf-rogue again.<br>
<br>
“I’ve been waiting for you both. Come. There is much to tell.”<br>
<br>
<br>
