<br>
<br>
<br>
Merribelle's feet kicked up little puffs of snow, blizzards in miniature over the valleys of her footprints. Grehan watched them in fascination as his friend and mentor paced before him in the unending whiteness.<br>
<br>
Ahead of her strode a legend, a lost heroine, a ghost - perhaps truly one, seeing her feet left no marks in the powder of fresh snow. Aeron Aodann; the foremother of all that the White Rose now was and the catalyst for all that it would be.<br>
<br>
Grehan's beard looked grey through it's frosting of ice-crystals and he brushed at it nervously, struggling through snow a foot thick after the two women. If Aeron left no mark of her passage, and Merri's inch-deep prints filled quickly with snow, his own marks were obvious and unsubtle, stretching out behind him in the frozen landscape. What had history and heroism to do with him? He was only a novice, a scout, a whelp in Cappi McTarnigal's words. He stumbled, and Merri, without looking reached back her hand to help him.<br>
<br>
&quot;Not far now,&quot; Aeron said from ahead of them. Merribelle's usually inscrutable countenance showed something like relief, and Grehan knew that had his cheeks not been stiff with cold he would have been smiling. <br>
<br>
Merri hauled Grehan to his feet with a strength that was a constant surprise to him, her light frame concealing more power than many of his comrades. She had pushed the fur of her hood back, and the gilt-smoothness of her long hair, frosted with ice-crystals, glinted in the fading light, adding to the contradiction; he knew there was little fragility in her. <br>
<br>
As they struggled through the snow, Grehan dwelled on that incongruity. One would not think this tiny creature to have the strength she did. Hearing her laugh, one would not notice the hardness of her will. Looking at her impish-pretty face you'd never guess the things that wracked the soul. He'd known her for more than a year, seen her in all moods, hunted with her, held her when she woke up screaming at middlenight. But whether he really knew her? He could not answer. Why she had followed him out here and why he now followed her on into the deepening dark, that question too was unanswered. Perhaps Aeron Aodann could tell him.<br>
<br>
His introspection ended when Aeron took his arm and led him to a low opening in the cliff-face they had followed for a mile. Shielded by low, hardy evergreens and blizzard-scarred rocks, he had to stoop almost to his knees to enter, though Merribelle followed him in merely bending her head. The cavern was black before him, and Grehan had to trust to the woman clutching his arm; his elf-friend was not so hampered by the darkness. They walked some little way and turned a corner, the passage narrowed, and then Grehan saw firelight ahead of him.<br>
<br>
Suddenly tired and hungry and lost, he could have wept when his guide led him to the fireplace and bade him sit.<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------<br>
<br>
<br>
The cavern was smallish, but had a high ceiling, to Merri’s relief. The smoke-stained gray rock of the wall showed many years of fires, the packed dirt floor and rustic though comfortable furniture spoke time and effort to make the place habitable. And Aeron Aodann stood in the middle of the cavern, her face as expressionless as a statue’s and at the same time alive with energy. Merri looked at the woman with curiosity she could not conceal. Grehan, on the other hand, stood still at the door, as though unable to come any closer to his hostess.<br>
<br>
When the barbarian woman finally spoke, her voice was warm with emotion, and if Grehan had been surprised before he was now awestruck, for Aeron was crying. “You have no notion how glad I am to have you both here at last,” she said softly, her voice creating muted echoes in the cavern. “My time alone has not been in vain but it has been lonely; and now, for a time at least, I have the company of two after my own heart.” The tall woman turned towards the crackling hearth, and two low stools that stood near it. “Take your rest, Merribelle, Grehan. I’ll bring food and mead, and when you are warm and fed I will tell you why you both are here.”<br>
<br>
As though sleepwalking, Grehan shuffled to a stool and sat down, staring deep into the flickering fireplace. Merri watched her host work swiftly in the corner nearest the fireplace for a moment before succumbing to the lure of warmth. Propping her toes on the very hearthstones, and lifting numb fingers to the radiance, she stared at her hands as the color returned to them, noting the thin cris-cross line of scars she’d earned earlier that summer on the Tundra. Her grin fought its way out through a face still stiff with cold, and the wolfish gleam in her eyes caught firelight; the orc that had drawn his scimitar across her hand had squealed quite satisfactorily when her dagger tore through the veins around his heart.<br>
<br>
As suddenly as the remembrance came to her, she was sickened by it. She had never truly enjoyed killing; of course there was the exhilaration of battle, the singing in her blood as she blurred through combat like a whirlwind of blades, the thrill of danger and victory. Only once before that orc had opened her hand from wrist to ring-finger she had ever felt the need to exact pain in return for pain. She pushed the memory of Machil's blood seeping over her fingertips back down before that unholy joy could take hold again, bringing with it the memories of what came after...<br>
<br>
Aeron nudged her consideration away from the threadfine line of scarring by placing a mug in the hand and a bowl in her lap.  Merri nodded thanks. &quot;You know what my first opinion of mead was, Grehan?&quot; Merri said lightly, looking down at the fire-warmed tankard brimming with tawny liquor. &quot;That here truly was the drink of Bristlebane himself... for only my tricksome lord could turn honey to something so sour.&quot;<br>
<br>
Grehan's appreciation for the humor was tempered by his nerves, for across the open hearth from the young Barbarian sat a living legend, and he attempted to hide his nerves in draining his own flagon. But the deep, honeyed chuckle of the White Rose surprised him.<br>
<br>
Aeron's eyes were alight with humor when Merri looked up at her. &quot;I see you have little trouble drinking it now, however, Merribelle...&quot;<br>
<br>
The feir'dal grinned and sipped the warmed liquor. &quot;Now how could one of Bristlebane's daughters let him get away with a trick like that? I love mead to spite him, of course.&quot;<br>
<br>
Again the deep, rich laugh rang out through the small cavern, and the woodelven rogue smiled, and drained half the mug of honeywine without stopping to consider its strength. Aeron grinned down at her, and gestured at the bowl. “Better eat some of that stew, Merribelle Stealshearts, to ballast you.” Grehan could not talk but could easily eat, and he smiled, already halfway through his meal and obviously enjoying it. As they ate, Aeron drew up a third seat to the fireplace, and placed it where she could best see her guest’s faces. Grehan was obviously forgetting his discomfort in the food, but Merri, the elf-girl, was watching her equally, her eyes hooded, flicking back and forth from the bowl to her face.<br>
<br>
Warm, fed and safe from the howling blizzard outside, she seemed at ease, even relaxed, but Grehan, whose own nerves were wound tighter than lute strings, could see she was no such thing. The tankard was on the floor next to her boot – in easy reach of the blades hidden in those black scaled articles - and her eyes remained hard and reflective in the firelight.  Something had Merri's senses on edge, and he would be wise to keep his head.<br>
<br>
Aeron Aodann was not blind to the readiness in her foreign guest. Sighing with reluctance, she put her own flagon down and looked earnestly across the fireplace at Merri, whose air of relaxation suddenly dissipated. &quot;Your instincts are excellent, Merri, but the threat I carry is in the future, not to you here and now. If you will listen with patience I will try to explain. Please, relax. Lay down your weapons and make yourself comfortable; your lives are as sacred here as though the Tribunal themselves had brought you. As my guests I would die myself before letting harm come to you.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;A threat is a threat, Aeron Aodann. That it comes in the morning or tonight before the fire cools is no excuse to close my eyes to it now... but I will hear you, that much at least is owed you for your hospitality.&quot; <br>
<br>
Aeron nodded and sighed, as though she could expect little more. “I’ve been alone in this place for a lifetime of my people, my friends. I am no threat to any one by my own will, not even to the disloyal who rule my kin in Halas. I doubt I could take rein again over my guild, for I have been in isolation too long to expect or deal with what they are capable of. However, the stories that are told carry part of the truth: the White Rose is to return to Halas.”<br>
<br>
Grehan’s eyes widened and his lips pressed together in a grim line. “McTarnigal will not tolerate yer return, lady. He runs Halas, or nearly, with his iron grip on th’ information the scouts bring in, and the trade he… organizes with the guilds in Qeynos and Highkeep…”<br>
<br>
“I am aware of the knife my lieutenant’s grandson holds to the throat of the Council, dear one.” <br>
<br>
“Then how?  And if ya’ll forgive the askin’, Why?”<br>
<br>
Aeron’s eyes were on the fireplace, the shadows of her hair hiding her expression, and she paused a long moment before answering. “When I was lady of the guild, we had but two motives: the will of the Tribunal through stealth, and the will of the Tribunal through slaughter. Our skills were for the good of all, and our place was clear and honored among our people. I remember it well that a young one might say they wished to join our ranks openly and the approval of their kin would be instant.” Grehan frowned, remembering his own family’s reluctance, and how his age-mates mocked him as a coward and weakling and fool. Aeron went on; “Even among the other races, the purpose of our kind is diluted slowly as the years pass. The honored Scouts of Kelethin meet repudiation from many of their own, as do the children of Brell. The Humans dismiss their rogue-kin entirely, and the dark ones themselves view the Ebon Hand as mere tools, unworthy to be kept past the doing of their task.”<br>
<br>
“But yet, the power of the many shadowed guilds across Antonica grows daily; but not for the work we were meant to complete! No, they grow fat on thievery, on murder and power and blood. Their numbers swell daily with those whose hearts hold greed and not honor, and the corruption has not left the Tribunal’s children untouched. Cappi McTarnigal is a blind fool, an unwitting pawn in the tide which has caught us all up.”<br>
<br>
The hiss of her breath and the clatter of stool, bowl and tankard broke Merri’s silence as she rose abruptly. “Pawn? Are not we all pawns, Aeron Aodann? I have been a pawn for as long as I’ve lived, and here you seek to put me back into play, in yet another game. Whose hand on the pieces this time, White Rose?”<br>
<br>
“Merri, calm, please! Aeron did not say that you had any role – “ Grehan started, but Aeron silenced him with a soft word.<br>
<br>
“Merri is right, kinsman; why bring you both here if you had no part to play in the game? Only in one thing is she wrong: before she had no choice. A pawn she was indeed, blind and moved by many hands and never at her own will. But in this game she must choose to play, and if she does, she may yet be a queen.”<br>
<br>
“Or I may choose to kick over the table” hissed the feir’dal. Snatching up her cloak and Grehan’s spear, she fled out into the storm.<br>
<br>
“Let her go,” Aeron said softly when Grehan rose to bring her back. “She will come to no harm.”<br>
<br>
Grehan stared down the narrow passageway to the tundra and shook his head. “I don’t understand, lady. You say you return to Halas. How does that change what the guilds have become? And why must Merri hold any part of that?”<br>
<br>
“Nothing is so complex that a knife can’t find it’s heart, Grehan, not even the heart of that corruption my guild has become. Merribelle will be my knife.&quot;<br>
<br>
----------------------------------<br>
<br>
Outside in the bitter cold, the storm was dying; its last gasps of force the dying breaths of its violence. Still, it was cold enough that the hot angry tears froze on Merri's cheeks, and she shivered in the deep fur of the cloak as she paced, irresolute, on the edge of the tundra.<br>
<br>
&quot;I was free here..&quot; she whispered softly, the wind stealing the words before she could hear them. &quot;I thought I was free. But now someone else wants to use me, use my skills, and something in me<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  wants</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to be of use. Mad Lord! Am I insane too?&quot;<br>
<br>
The dying tempest was not listening; almost noone was - and none that would help. Hauling herself up from her knees with the spear to lean on, Merribelle Stealshearts walked achingly back to the cavern, the warmth, and the game.<br>
<br>
The ice elemental, it's rudimentary eyes being used by its master, followed as close as it dared to the entrance, then dissolved into crystals, just like the snow. The one who used its eyes rose from concealment on a hill a mile distant. He tightened the sorcerous cape about him, instinctively, for it did not allow the cold to touch him. Then, with a whispered word, his form seemed to dissolve also, only to reform back in Felwithe, beside the roaring warmth of a fireplace.<br>
<br>
